
---

## 2. Add a LICENSE (Highly Recommended)

On GitHub:

- Go to your repository.
- Click **Add file → Create new file**.
- Name it `LICENSE`.
- Click **Choose a license template**.
- Select **MIT License**.
- Commit the file.

MIT is a good default for most open-source projects.

---

## 3. Make sure your repository has

- ✅ Public visibility
- ✅ README.md
- ✅ LICENSE
- ✅ Source code (not just the built website)
- ✅ A few meaningful commits
- ✅ A project description (optional but helpful)

---

## 4. Wait a few minutes

After adding the README and LICENSE, GitHub may take a little time to update metadata. Then refresh the Claude form and try again.

### One more thing

I looked at your repository name, but I **can't confirm from here** whether the repository actually contains source code or is mainly the generated GitHub Pages site.

If you want to maximize your chances of getting Claude for Open Source, I can review your repository and tell you:
- what's missing,
- what should be improved,
- and whether it looks like a strong open-source project.

That will give you a much better chance of approval.
